      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions used for validation must be documented and traceable to the COU operating envelope.",
      "rationale": "Bench tests were conducted at five flow-speed combinations (2.5–5 L/min; 2000–3500 RPM) spanning the CPB operating envelope. Fluid temperature, hematocrit, and inlet pressure boundary conditions are documented in the validation data package. Required level 2 is met."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model predictions of the normalised index of hemolysis (NIH) must agree with experimental measurements within ±20% across all five operating points.",
      "rationale": "CFD-predicted NIH values compared against plasma-free haemoglobin measurements from bench tests. Maximum deviation across five operating points is 14.7%. All predictions fall within the ±20% acceptance band. Required level 2 is met."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The QoIs used in the model (scalar stress-based hemolysis index, RH) must be directly linked to the clinical endpoint of red blood cell damage during CPB.",
      "rationale": "The scalar stress hemolysis model (Giersiepen–Wurzinger power-law) maps directly to the relative hemolysis index RH used in the regulatory submission. RH < 1 is the accepted surrogate for non-inferiority to the predicate device. Relevance is established. Required level 2 is met."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
